body:
Hi!

We are developing a course at our uni and we are switching over to verilator, 
from previously running on commercial tools.
I believe I encountered a case in which verilator is not working as expected.

This issue might be related to https://github.com/verilator/verilator/issues/4529 , but I'm not sure


This RTL (alu.sv):

```systemverilog
module add2 #(parameter int N = 3)
  (input [N-1:0] d0, d1,
   output [N-1:0] y);

  assign y = d1 + d0;
endmodule

module sub3 #(parameter int N = 3)
  (input [N-1:0] d0, d1, d2,
   output [N-1:0] y);

  wire [N-1:0] output_ab, output_bc;

  add2 #(N) ab( .d0(d0), .d1(d1), .y(output_ab));
  add2 #(N) bc( .d0(d1), .d1(d2), .y(output_bc));
  assign y = output_ab - output_bc;

endmodule
```
</details>

With this testbench (tb_mux4.sv) :


```systemverilog
`include "alu.sv"

// Code your testbench here
// or browse Examples
module tb_mux4 ();
  // mux4 tests
  reg [8:0] d0, d1, d2;
  wire [8:0] Y;

  sub3 #(9) dut(.d0(d0), .d1(d1), .d2(d2), .y(Y));

  initial begin
    // mux4 tests
        d0 = 9'b000000000; d1 = 9'b000001000; d2 = 9'b000010000;
  end
endmodule
```


compiles just fine with
```
verilator --binary --timing --trace --assert -j 0 -Wno-MULTITOP tb_mux4.sv
```
However, if I add the rest of the alu.sv file:


```systemverilog
module add2 #(parameter int N = 3)
  (input [N-1:0] d0, d1,
   output [N-1:0] y);

  assign y = d1 + d0;
endmodule

module sub3 #(parameter int N = 3)
  (input [N-1:0] d0, d1, d2,
   output [N-1:0] y);

  wire [N-1:0] output_ab, output_bc;

  add2 #(N) ab( .d0(d0), .d1(d1), .y(output_ab));
  add2 #(N) bc( .d0(d1), .d1(d2), .y(output_bc));
  assign y = output_ab - output_bc;

endmodule

module somethingelse #(parameter int N = 3) // maybe implement this differently
  (input [N-1:0] d0, d1, d2, d3,
   output [N-1:0] y);

  wire [N-1:0] output_sub3;

  sub3 #(N) lowmux(.d0(d0), .d1(d1), .d2(d2), .y(output_sub3));
  assign y = output_sub3 + d3;
endmodule
```

Verilator seems to not be able to see that the parameters in add2 are "transitively" set in sub3?

```
verilator --binary --timing --trace --assert -j 0 -Wno-MULTITOP tb_mux4.sv
%Warning-WIDTHTRUNC: alu.sv:14:18: Input port connection 'd0' expects 3 bits on the pin connection, but pin connection's VARREF 'd0' generates 9 bits.
